Hi Pat!

In this situation, you can use the [`filter_cssFIlter` option](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/example-widget-filter.html#filter-css-filter) to add a class name to the filter cell to hide it:

```css
.hidden { display: none; }
```

```js
// hiding the second & fourth columns
filter_cssFilter : [ '', 'hidden', '', 'hidden' ]
```

Really the easiest way to hide a column is to use a css selector like this:

```css
 /* hide <col> so set widths apply to correct columns*/
table col:nth-child(3),
table tr th:nth-child(3),
table tr td:nth-child(3) {
  display: none;
}
```

If you do want to save the filters, but only ignore it in some circumstances, you could set the `filter_saveFilters` to `false`, then set it to `true` after initialization:

```js
$('table').tablesorter({
  // ... other options
  widgetOptions : {
    filter_saveFilters: false
  },
  initialized: function(table) {
    table.config.widgetOptions.filter_saveFilters = true;
  }
});
```

I'm not sure how to do tests that cover this when they're also supposed to cover later devices unless you want to also define the product.  From the tests, it seems on your device the response for a 200 status is:
{"statusCode": 0, "message": "OK"}
on mine it is:
{ "statusCode":0,"message":"Action Successful"}

If I leave that bit of json out on the stop command I get:
{ "statusCode":6,"message":"Invalid request"}
but I'm pretty sure yours and newer devices would still return:
{"statusCode": 0, "message": "OK"}

Let me know what you think.

