@kyleknap, here is the initial iteration of the design you discussed. I wired up the models, and introspection now works (`client.meta.exceptions.<TAB>` produces expected results). Please take a look and let me know your feedback / things to finish up.

I would like to restrict the scope of the initial merge to produce subclasses for only those errors in the model, and push subclassing in the blind in a separate PR.

I ran into an annoying inconsistency - IAM and presumably some other services name their errors with the "Exception" suffix, e.g. NoSuchEntityException, but send `NoSuchEntity` on the wire instead. I've put in a secondary lookup hack to deal with this behavior, let me know if you can think of a better way.

@fgimian I don't think your Python 3 compatibility update got things quite right. I was using splinter 0.6.0 with webdriver under Python 3 and things worked, but after upgrading to 0.7.1 I am seeing many errors like this:
```
>       assert text in context.browser.title
E       TypeError: Type str doesn't support the buffer API
```

I don't think you should be decoding strings to bytes for the title or html. Instead just leave it as an encoded string:

    @property
    def title(self):
        if sys.version_info[0] > 2:
            return self.driver.title.encode('utf-8')
        else:
            return self.driver.title

https://github.com/cobrateam/splinter/commit/5d14dad0b43a7f396f9a9b2d0601ca27e8d78bfc?diff=unified#diff-57bd95ad52ad7f3fc6217684677d0576R43

If a different driver returns a bytes object then in probably should be decoded to a string.

for now, using `platform_release` might work, since that's different in dev and prod:
```
"psycopg2" = { version = "*", platform_release = "==4.4.0-1065-aws" }
```

