Ok, I added a progress bar that calls update whenever its progress is modified:

```
class AutoupdatingProgressBar(ProgressBar):
    @property
    def progress(self):
        return self._progress
    
    @progress.setter
    def progress(self, value):
        self._progress = value
        self.update()
```

The horse race at the end now uses this version, so doesn't have to keep calling update.

OKAY. SO. This really sucks and I want to go home.

Here's a testcase:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <fenv.h>

int main() {
    float x, y;
    x = 0.1;
    y = 0.2;
    float a, b, c, d;
    fesetround(FE_TONEAREST);
    a = x + y;
    fesetround(FE_UPWARD);
    b = x + y;
    fesetround(FE_DOWNWARD);
    c = x + y;
    fesetround(FE_TOWARDZERO);
    d = x + y;
    printf("%x\n%x\n%x\n%x\n", *(int*)&a, *(int*)&b, *(int*)&c, *(int*)&d);
    return 0;
}
```

It prints this out:

```
3e99999a
3e99999a
3e999999
3e999999
```

As expected. Note that this doesn't work if compiled for x86-32 since that'll use the 80-bit x87 registers for math and maintain all precision all the time.

Now, if you disassemble this program and look for the specific constants that are being used for 0.1 and 0.2, you see `3DCCCCCD` and `3E4CCCCD`.

Now, if you reproduce this as a claripy script as was done above, and then do some hacking into the internals to print out the specific representations being used, you see that 0.1 and 0.2 are being represented as `3DCCCCCC` and `3E4CCCCC`. These can be added together without losing any precision.

If you switch the above example to using doubles instead of floats you do in fact see the intended divergent behavior. I'm pretty sure the discrepancy is because we obtain that constant by parsing 0.1 as a double, then converting it to a float.

I never want to think about this ever again.

