@istoica Sorry for late response, we set up several meetings in our side to discuss the whole streaming support base on your proposal. We have a whole design for the streaming now. 
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1EubVMFSFJqNLmbNztnYKj6m0VMzg3a8ZVQZg-mgbLQ0/edit#
The main idea is the streaming layer will be an individual layer on ray just as ray tune. It will start actors on ray and provide the high level API just like join, split to users(We will try to make it compatible with Flink or Spark API for quick on-boarding). The FO also be encapsulated in these actors. The plasma queue will be transparent to user application.

@1st1: I don't care about `partial` magically working; I just want it to be possible for it to work :-). Basically I think it should be possible for wrappers/partials/decorators to work, but it should require some intentional action on the part of the person writing the wrapper. (And of course `functools.partial` should take this action.)

> Instead of looking at the last frame you can traverse until you see `f_inawait`. Isn't ideal though.

I don't think this works, because in practically any context where you can potentially forget an `await`, you'd have *some* frame in your callstack that has `f_inawait` set.

@SemanticBeeng I apologize if this is overly pedantic but I want to be accurate. I'm not sure invoke is quite as black and white as you make it to be, for example the following code prints `2`
```
  public static void main(String[] args) throws JepException{
    try(Jep jep = new Jep()) {
        jep.eval("class TheClass(object):\n" +
                 "    @staticmethod\n" +
                 "    def theStaticMethod(arg):" +
                 "        return arg + 1\n");
        jep.eval("tmp = TheClass.theStaticMethod");
        Object result = jep.invoke("tmp", 1);
        System.out.println(result);
    }
  }
```
Technically `tmp` is still a staticmethod, and I wouldn't consider it to be a "top level function", technically you can `invoke()` any callable python obect. However for things like methods of objects or `staticmethod` most people are used to accessing it with the `.` notation and calling it all in one statement and that doesn't currently work in `invoke()`.

I don't understand what you are saying about the dataLayerModule. I don't think it particularly matters to jep how you import a module. A workaround mentioned earlier in this thread is to just import the attributes from the module, so for your example something like this might let you invoke `connect()` easier:

```
jep.eval("from modules.data_layer import connect");
jep.invoke("connect", somePlace);
```

